page.title: 12Place names in Silverdale
page.content: {Jenny Brown's Point}- The origin is uncertain, but a man with the surname Brown farmed there in the sixteenth century, so it may originate from then. {Jack Scout}- probably meant oaktree cliff {Cow's Mouth}- the meaning is obscure, but this break in the cliffs was used by drovers crossing the Kent with cattle for the Lancashire markets. {Quicksand Pool}- The whole area is notorious for dangerous quicksands, and this must once have been such. {Quakers Stang}- Stang is an old name for pool, so it is reasonable to assume that this too derives from quicksand.
